<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-06-25T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="321" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d321">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72113/606</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The French Ambassador</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_JJJ1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Jusserand</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Translation]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-06-25">
                                    <hi rend="italic">June 25, 1918</hi></date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received June 28.</hi>]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mr. Secretary of State</hi>: The Minister of France
                            at Rio asked, jointly with his colleagues of England and Belgium,
                            several weeks ago, the Brazilian Government to make an engagement that
                            it would <pb facs="0388" n="304" xml:id="pg_304"/> not rescind the
                            measures taken with regard to private enemy property, except after
                            consultation with the Allied Powers.</p>
                        <p>The Minister of Foreign Affairs of Brazil answered that he had no
                            objection in principle to that proposition, but especially desired to
                            know whether the United States would be disposed to make, in so far as
                            it is concerned, an engagement of the same nature.</p>
                        <p>I should be thankful to Your Excellency if you would kindly acquaint me
                            with the views of the Federal Government on the subject.<note n="1" xml:id="d321fn1">Note in Department file: “It was decided not to
                                reply to this note because it was requested that if our answer was
                                ‘No’ we not reply.”</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>Be pleased to accept [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_JJJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Jusserand</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>